    "statement": "Suppose f: R → R is a continuous function such that f'(x) > 0 for all x ∈ R. Then, f is unbounded.",
    "proof": "Since f'(x) > 0 for all x ∈ R, the function f is strictly increasing. Therefore, for any given M ∈ R, there exists x_M ∈ R such that f(x) > M for all x > x_M, hence f is unbounded."
